[{"sha":"a297cd670d58149763d3eba82b626a4e9d5c55da","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Disable MLIR bridge in the second phase for non entry functions

Currently, the MLIR bridge is enabled based on the graph analysis for each function individually so it may happen that a parent function is not compiled with MLIR but function attached to any op like WhileOp in the function is compiled with MLIR. This makes the logic complex and can expose new bugs if we disable MLIR bridge in the first phase.

The downside of this is that second phase of the bridge will be rolled out slowly and with coarser grained forks. This is what we want in the beginning to limit bridge rollout to the first phase and later this can be tweaked, if required.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 359640757
Change-Id: I768e6cff5e38dcef781eab3305692dd73d599f94","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/a297cd670d58149763d3eba82b626a4e9d5c55da"}]

[{"sha":"6cd9552206b498ca6af04722e0749a6e4cf26a15","author":{"name":"Frederic Bastien","email":"f97faf633e0f27948feb654f3e29ab2be0f12d06@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Allows loading textual LLVM IR from a file instead of the one generated by XLA codegen.

This helps prototyping some LLVM IR without the need to change XLA code
emitter.

How to use:
- Get an module_NNNN.ir-no-opt.ll file from XLA.
- Copy that to a new file named module_NNNN.ANYTHING.ll
- Modify it to the LLVM IR that you want to prototype.
- Then pass that new file to XLA with:
  XLA_FLAGS=--xla_gpu_llvm_ir_file=module_NNNN.ANYTHING.ll

[{"sha":"068a488441cb23f9e1ea584007588e7c9f6ffb75","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: A better error message for custom variable validation

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the

[{"sha":"54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: A better error message for custom variable validation

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"}]

[{"sha":"012cdb54e29771e0581c09f1193c9919ba053d7b","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/012cdb54e29771e0581c09f1193c9919ba053d7b"},{"sha":"ffed2c50821508f2b4447c3577d02a9420665915","author":{"name":"The Terraform Team","email":"2a56ea1490dced68c01a1ee616138a226895907a@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge 012cdb54e29771e0581c09f1193c9919ba053d7b into backport/f-minimal-language-editions/exactly-creative-mustang","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ffed2c50821508f2b4447c3577d02a9420665915"}]

[{"sha":"b364f77d31090c0578b2413321af59db4af7c498","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"While body/cond region block arguments should match the arguments of cond/while functions.

In most cases, the WhileOp operand, cond operand, body operand and WhileOp result should have the same shape.  However in the case WhileOps with the attribute shape_invariant the WhileOp result, cond operand, and body operand will match but the WhileOp operand may have a different, compatible shape.  This changes the block argument used to match the function signature of the cond/body function when converting from functional to region control flow.
